}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 135-136.}{\plain \fs24   These final verses of the canto have drawn numerous attempts at a clear \softline
understanding.  However, without knowing the precise nature of the facts to which Dante has \softline
decided to allude, we cannot be certain.  Among the more interesting suggestions for a source is \softline
Hermann Gmelin's (}{\plain \fs24 \i Kommentar: der L{\f1\u228\'e4}uterungsberg}{\plain \fs24  [Stuttgart: Klett, 1955], }{\plain \fs24 \i ad loc}{\plain \fs24 .): the verses \softline
reflect Dido's remark about her dead husband, Sichaeus, at }{\plain \fs24 \i Aeneid}{\plain \fs24  IV.28-29: 'ille meos, }{\plain \fs24 \i primus \softline
qui me sibi iunxit}{\plain \fs24 , amores / abstulit; ille habeat secum servetque sepulchro' (He, who first joined \softline
me to him, has sealed up my love; may he have it with him and keep it in his grave).  The \softline
italicized phrase seems close enough to Dante's 'colui che 'nnanellata pria / disposando' to merit \softline
further thought, even if the contexts are not the same, a suffering wife and murderous husband \softline
replacing a loyal husband and a would-be loyal wife.  Did Pia's husband himself give her a ring \softline
of betrothal before they married or, as Varanini suggests, did the man who eventually killed her, \softline
the representative of her husband (one Magliata di Pionpino), present the ring for him?\par
